To maximize the current capacity of the NbTi wires (i.e. critical current), and to enable operation in persistent current mode, the superconducting magnets are cooled to temperatures well below the critical temperature K. Typically, NbTi based MRI magnets are operated at temperature of 4.2 K by completely submersing the magnet coils in a LHe bath.
The superconductor is operated below both the transition temperature of MgB2 of 39 K and the critical current value at the desired magnetic field and temperature so that no power loss occurs.
